    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.7-9_0001" />
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    The New York Times
                        <lb/>
                    Times Square
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">OFFICE OF
                        <lb/>
                    THE EDITOR OF
                        <lb/>
                    THE BOOK REVIEW</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>20 Septr 1911</dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It is quite too bad if the brief note (the wording of which I confess having <unclear/>) I sent you in reference to "Emerson's Wife" should lead you to believe that I sought to impose restrictions of any kind upon you. My sole interest was to inform you of the authorship. If my note was so unfortunately worded as
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.7-9_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">8</fw>
                    
                to suggest a favorable review against your judgement I am very sorry. I should much appreciate a note from you which will <unclear>give</unclear> the text of my letter. I have <unclear/> sought to suggest, ever, that a review should <unclear>go wide</unclear> of this frank opinion in the matter of a book. Books that are sent to you or to any other reviewer are sent to provoke the reviewer's candid view; the <title>Review</title> will print no
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.7-9_0003a"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">9</fw>
                    
                other kind. The last book of Mrs. Kelly's <unclear/> in the <title>Review</title> was criticized unsparingly, so you are the entire independance of our publication. There have been several instances in which I had <unclear>preferred</unclear> that a book be praised but the review <unclear>sent</unclear> in was far from favorable to it &#8212; yet the review was published just as written. I feel it no <unclear/> of which to say to a reviewer,
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.7-9_0003b"/>
                    
                "I hope you can praise this book" or "I should like to read a favorable review of <unclear>this if</unclear> it be <unclear>possible</unclear> to write it," where it is my <unclear>intention</unclear> to publish the review <hi rend="underline">whatever</hi> opinion it expresses. When I write you at any time about a book, do not <unclear/> it as <unclear>buttering</unclear> you hand in any way. Books sent you are, as you know, to be reviewed as you see fit.</p>
                <closer>
                   <salute>Very truly yours</salute>
                    
                   <signed>George Buchanan <unclear/></signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
